{
  "monologue": "Using a small, low-friction action when urges peak leverages the user's need for structure and reduces decision fatigue, helping maintain adherence and progress toward a steadier routine. Rotating micro-actions avoids boredom and supports BED management by pairing action with urge logging.",
  "utterance": "Tonight, start with your two-minute diaphragmatic breathing as the anchor. If the urge remains around your current level, add a fresh 60-second micro-action you can do in place: 30 seconds of ankle circles and 30 seconds of gentle torso twists, then resume your stretches for another minute. Log your urge and mood after the session. This ultra-simple, rotating sequence helps you stay on track and move toward a steadier BED-management rhythm.",
  "endkey": false
}
